column1: #Text=Many people of France regard their cuisine to be the best in the world .
#Text=France is the origin of the Guide Michelin rating system , and ties Japan ( which has twice the population ) for the highest number of stars in the guidebook .
#Text=French cuisine has set a standard for fine dining around the world , and menus in high-end Western restaurants are often printed in French .
#Text=French cuisine has roots back to the Roman Empire .
#Text=Influenced by Italian cuisine as well as local traditions , haute cuisine was created in Paris during the Early Modern times .
#Text=The French Revolution put an end to guilds and the privileged noble class , expanding fine cooking and dining to common people .

#Text=While foreign cuisines such as Mexican food , American fast food and Chinese food have been less successful in France than in other parts of Europe , they can be found in Paris and the other more cosmopolitan cities .
#Text=, Vietnamese and Middle Eastern cuisine s are among those that have been imported from former French colonies and taken root in the former mother country .
#Text=At least some North African food has been fully assimilated , as a survey in the 1990s found that couscous was the most popular French food ( so described by the respondents ) in France .

#Text=Conversely , French cuisine has also influenced the cuisines of its former colonial possessions , with the cuisines of Quebec and Louisiana having a strong French influence , albeit with the incorporation of many local North American flavours and ingredients , and a modified version of the French baguette has been widely adopted in Vietnam for use in the ubiquitous bánh mì sandwiches .
#Text=( petit déjeuner ) in France is n't the most important meal of the day , and is usually very light .

#Text=The most typical breakfast consists of a coffee and a croissant or some other " viennoiserie " , but since it implies going to the boulangerie early in the morning to buy fresh croissants , it 's typically reserved for somewhat special occasions .

#Text=On normal days most people have a beverage ( coffee , tea , hot chocolate , orange juice ) and either toast ( " tartines " made of baguette or toast bread with butter and jam/honey/Nutella ) that can be dipped in the hot beverage , or cereals with milk .
#Text=People who eat healthy may go for fruit and yoghurt .
#Text=As a general rule , the French breakfast is mostly sweet , but anything can change and you can have savoury breakfasts everywhere today .
#Text=Both lunch ( déjeuner ) and dinner ( dîner ) are traditionally full meals .
#Text=They often consist of an appetiser ( entrée or hors d'œuvre ) , a main dish ( plat ) , and a dessert ( dessert ) or cheese .
#Text=( pain ) is the classical side order in France .
#Text=The baguette , a plain wheat roll , is the archetypal bread .
#Text=( fromage ) comes in hundreds of varieties , and can be included in most dishes .
#Text=Here is a far from exhaustive list of what one can find :
#Text=has made broad strides in the first two decades of the 21st century , and while restaurants with at least one veggie option used to be the exception they are now the rule .
#Text=Meanwhile more and more cartes feature at least one vegan ( végétalien ) item .
#Text=Every French region has dishes all its own .
#Text=These dishes follow the resources ( game , fish , agriculture , etc. ) of the region , the vegetables ( cabbage , turnip , endives , etc. ) which they grow there .
#Text=Here is a small list of regional dishes which you can find easily in France .
#Text=Generally each region has a unique and widespread dish ( usually because it was food for the masses ) :
#Text=( Southwest France ) : beans , duck , pork & sausages
#Text=, or sauerkraut ( Alsace ) : stripped fermented cabbage + pork
#Text=( central Alps ) : melted/hot cheese with white wine
#Text=( Burgundy ) : pieces of beef ( in boiled oil ) , usually served with a selection of various sauces .
#Text=( found all over France ) : boiled beef with vegetables
#Text=( Burgundy ) : slow cooked beef with red wine gravy
#Text=( Rhône-Alpes ) : oven-roasted slices of potatoes with sour cream and cheese
#Text=( Aveyron ) : melted cheese mixed with a purée of potatoes
#Text=( fish + saffron ) ( Marseille and the French Riviera ) .
#Text=Do n't be fooled ! A real bouillabaisse is a really expensive dish due to the amount of fresh fish it requires .
#Text=Be prepared to pay at least € 30 per person .
#Text=If you find restaurants claiming to serve bouillabaisse for something like € 15 per person , you 'll find it to be of a very poor quality .
#Text=( Savoie ) : Melted Reblochon cheese , potatoes and pork or bacon .
#Text=( south west ) : Duck Confit , consists of legs and wings bathing in grease .
#Text=That grease is actually very healthy and , with red wine , is one of the identified sources of the so-called " French Paradox " ( eat richly , live long ) .

#Text=Although usually quite expensive , foie gras can be found in supermarkets for a lower price ( because of their purchasing power ) around the Christmas season .
#Text=It is the time of year when most foie gras is consumed in France .
#Text=Mussels steamed in white wine , garlic and shallots , normally served with crusty bread and French fries ( moules-frites , which are Belgian in origin ) .
#Text=Add cream and sometimes lardons , then you 've got moules normandes .
#Text=Ditch the wine and cook in cider , and enjoy moules bretonnes .
#Text=Or throw in tomatoes and herbes de Provence ( savory , marjoram , rosemary , thyme , oregano ) for moules à la provençale .
